    "title": "Nocturnal Low-Level Jet",
    "subtitle": "CLAMPS2",
    "campaign": "NWC Ops",
    "location": "Oklahoma",
    "image": "images/nllj_c2_instrument_template_4panel.png",
    "tags": ["boundary layer", "nocturnal"],
    "sections": [
      {
        "type": "text",
        "title": "Case overview",
        "content": "A nocturnal low-level jet (NLLJ) sampled at the Norman, Oklahoma home base (NWC/NSSL). This is routine CLAMPS2 operations data from 2016 — not a BLISSFUL deployment (BLISSFUL was a separate 2021 Oklahoma campaign). After sunset the surface layer decouples and southwesterly flow accelerates into a wind-speed maximum a few hundred meters above ground. CLAMPS2 combines thermodynamic profiling (TROPoe / AERI–MWR), Doppler-lidar winds (WINDoe), and turbulence (DLFP) to capture the jet and the stable layer beneath it."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "title": "What to look for",
        "content": "In the overnight hours (roughly 03–12 UTC), Panel C shows a jet core near 0.5 km with speeds exceeding 15 m s⁻¹ and southwesterly barbs. Panels A and B show a shallow, stable, moist layer capped below ~0.3 km (fuzzy PBLH line). Panel D stays quiescent until afternoon, when deep mixing develops. Together this illustrates how CLAMPS resolves kinematic and thermodynamic structure through the stable-to-convective transition."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "title": "Instruments",
        "content": "θᵥ and water vapor: TROPoe (AERI + microwave radiometer). Horizontal wind: WINDoe VAD from DL-PPI. Turbulence: DLFP vertical-velocity variance (σ²_w, log scale). Black line on all panels: fuzzy PBL height estimate."
      }
    ]
  },
